# The deck as an Anki text-import file (headers set the notetype, deck, tag
# column and separator). Generated from mathgre/decks/mathgre_sample.tsv.
GRE_MATH_DECK_TSV = "#separator:tab\n#html:false\n#notetype:Basic\n#deck:GRE Math\n#tags column:3\nState the precise (ε–δ) definition of lim_{x→a} f(x) = L.\tFor every ε > 0 there exists δ > 0 such that if 0 < |x − a| < δ then |f(x) − L| < ε.\ttopic::calculus\nWhen is f continuous at x = a?\tf is continuous at a if f(a) is defined, lim_{x→a} f(x) exists, and lim_{x→a} f(x) = f(a).\ttopic::calculus\nEvaluate lim_{x→0} (sin x)/x.\t1\ttopic::calculus\nEvaluate lim_{x→0} (1 − cos x)/x.\t0\ttopic::calculus\nState the limit definition of the derivative f'(x).\tf'(x) = lim_{h→0} [f(x+h) − f(x)]/h.\ttopic::calculus\nProduct rule: d/dx[f(x)g(x)] = ?\tf'(x)g(x) + f(x)g'(x)\ttopic::calculus\nQuotient rule: d/dx[f(x)/g(x)] = ?\t[f'(x)g(x) − f(x)g'(x)] / g(x)^2\ttopic::calculus\nChain rule: d/dx[f(g(x))] = ?\tf'(g(x)) · g'(x)\ttopic::calculus\nd/dx[tan x] = ?\tsec^2 x\ttopic::calculus\nd/dx[ln x] = ?\t1/x\ttopic::calculus\nd/dx[e^x] = ?\te^x\ttopic::calculus\nd/dx[arctan x] = ?\t1/(1 + x^2)\ttopic::calculus\nd/dx[arcsin x] = ?\t1/√(1 − x^2)\ttopic::calculus\nState the Fundamental Theorem of Calculus (Part 1).\tIf f is continuous on [a,b] and F(x) = ∫_a^x f(t) dt, then F'(x) = f(x).\ttopic::calculus\nState the Fundamental Theorem of Calculus (Part 2, evaluation).\tIf f is continuous on [a,b] and F is any antiderivative of f, then ∫_a^b f(x) dx = F(b) − F(a).\ttopic::calculus\nIntegration by parts formula: ∫ u dv = ?\tuv − ∫ v du\ttopic::calculus\n∫ 1/x dx = ?\tln|x| + C\ttopic::calculus\n∫ sec^2 x dx = ?\ttan x + C\ttopic::calculus\n∫ 1/(1 + x^2) dx = ?\tarctan x + C\ttopic::calculus\n∫ e^x dx = ?\te^x + C\ttopic::calculus\nEvaluate ∫ x e^x dx.\tx e^x − e^x + C\ttopic::calculus\nSum of a convergent geometric series Σ_{n=0}^∞ a r^n (|r| < 1) = ?\ta/(1 − r)\ttopic::calculus\nFor which p does the p-series Σ_{n=1}^∞ 1/n^p converge?\tIt converges if and only if p > 1.\ttopic::calculus\nState the Ratio Test conclusion using L = lim_{n→∞} |a_{n+1}/a_n|.\tIf L < 1 the series converges absolutely; if L > 1 (or ∞) it diverges; if L = 1 the test is inconclusive.\ttopic::calculus\nState the Alternating Series Test.\tΣ (−1)^n b_n converges if b_n > 0, b_n is decreasing, and lim_{n→∞} b_n = 0.\ttopic::calculus\nMaclaurin series of e^x = ?\tΣ_{n=0}^∞ x^n/n! = 1 + x + x^2/2! + x^3/3! + ...\ttopic::calculus\nMaclaurin series of sin x = ?\tΣ_{n=0}^∞ (−1)^n x^(2n+1)/(2n+1)! = x − x^3/3! + x^5/5! − ...\ttopic::calculus\nMaclaurin series of cos x = ?\tΣ_{n=0}^∞ (−1)^n x^(2n)/(2n)! = 1 − x^2/2! + x^4/4! − ...\ttopic::calculus\nPower series of 1/(1 − x) for |x| < 1 = ?\tΣ_{n=0}^∞ x^n = 1 + x + x^2 + x^3 + ...\ttopic::calculus\nDefine the gradient ∇f of a scalar function f(x,y,z).\t∇f = (∂f/∂x, ∂f/∂y, ∂f/∂z), the vector of first partial derivatives.\ttopic::calculus\nFor z = f(x,y) with x = x(t), y = y(t), the chain rule gives dz/dt = ?\tdz/dt = (∂f/∂x)(dx/dt) + (∂f/∂y)(dy/dt)\ttopic::calculus\nGive the area element dA for a double integral in polar coordinates.\tdA = r dr dθ\ttopic::calculus\nState the Jacobian volume element for spherical coordinates (ρ, φ, θ).\tdV = ρ^2 sin φ dρ dφ dθ\ttopic::calculus\nState Green's Theorem.\t∮_C (P dx + Q dy) = ∬_D (∂Q/∂x − ∂P/∂y) dA, where C is the positively oriented boundary of region D.\ttopic::calculus\nState the Divergence Theorem.\t∬_S F · dS = ∭_V (∇ · F) dV, where S is the closed boundary surface of solid region V.\ttopic::calculus\nState Stokes' Theorem.\t∮_C F · dr = ∬_S (∇ × F) · dS, where C is the boundary of surface S with compatible orientation.\ttopic::calculus\nGive the arc length of y = f(x) from x = a to x = b.\tL = ∫_a^b √(1 + (f'(x))^2) dx\ttopic::calculus\nVolume of revolution about the x-axis (disk method) for y = f(x), a ≤ x ≤ b = ?\tV = π ∫_a^b (f(x))^2 dx\ttopic::calculus\nSolve the separable ODE dy/dx = k y.\ty = C e^(k x)\ttopic::calculus\nGive the integrating factor for the linear ODE y' + P(x) y = Q(x).\tμ(x) = e^(∫ P(x) dx)\ttopic::calculus\nFor a 2x2 matrix A = [[a, b], [c, d]], what is det(A)?\tdet(A) = ad − bc\ttopic::linear-algebra\nHow do you expand det of a 3x3 matrix [[a,b,c],[d,e,f],[g,h,i]] along the first row?\tdet = a(ei − fh) − b(di − fg) + c(dh − eg)\ttopic::linear-algebra\nWhen is a square matrix A invertible? Give several equivalent conditions.\tA is invertible ⇔ det(A) ≠ 0 ⇔ rank = n (full rank) ⇔ columns are linearly independent ⇔ 0 is not an eigenvalue ⇔ Ax = 0 has only the trivial solution\ttopic::linear-algebra\nState the rank-nullity theorem for a linear map T: V → W with V finite-dimensional.\tdim(V) = rank(T) + nullity(T), i.e. dim(V) = dim(im T) + dim(ker T)\ttopic::linear-algebra\nWhat is a basis of a vector space, and what is the dimension?\tA basis is a linearly independent set that spans the space; the dimension is the number of vectors in any basis (all bases have the same size)\ttopic::linear-algebra\nDefine an eigenvalue and eigenvector of a matrix A.\tA nonzero vector v with Av = λv for a scalar λ; λ is the eigenvalue and v is an eigenvector\ttopic::linear-algebra\nHow is the characteristic polynomial of an n×n matrix A defined?\tp(λ) = det(A − λI); its roots are the eigenvalues of A\ttopic::linear-algebra\nWhen is an n×n matrix diagonalizable (over a field)?\tA is diagonalizable ⇔ it has n linearly independent eigenvectors ⇔ for every eigenvalue its geometric multiplicity equals its algebraic multiplicity\ttopic::linear-algebra\nRelate trace and determinant of A to its eigenvalues (with multiplicity).\ttrace(A) = sum of eigenvalues; det(A) = product of eigenvalues\ttopic::linear-algebra\nIs matrix multiplication commutative? State the rule for when AB is defined.\tNo, in general AB ≠ BA; AB is defined when A is m×n and B is n×p, giving an m×p matrix\ttopic::linear-algebra\nHow do elementary row operations affect a determinant?\tSwapping two rows multiplies det by −1; scaling a row by k multiplies det by k; adding a multiple of one row to another leaves det unchanged\ttopic::linear-algebra\nWhen are two vectors u and v orthogonal?\tWhen their dot product is zero: u · v = 0\ttopic::linear-algebra\nGive the cross product formula for a = (a1,a2,a3) and b = (b1,b2,b3) in R^3.\ta × b = (a2 b3 − a3 b2, a3 b1 − a1 b3, a1 b2 − a2 b1); it is orthogonal to both a and b\ttopic::linear-algebra\nGive the dot product formula and its geometric meaning.\tu · v = u1 v1 + u2 v2 + ... + un vn = |u| |v| cos θ, where θ is the angle between u and v\ttopic::linear-algebra\nWhat is the idea behind the Gram-Schmidt process?\tIt converts a linearly independent set into an orthogonal (or orthonormal) basis by subtracting from each vector its projections onto the previously constructed vectors\ttopic::linear-algebra\nFor Ax = b, how do rank(A) and rank([A|b]) determine solvability?\tConsistent ⇔ rank(A) = rank([A|b]); then unique solution if rank = number of unknowns, infinitely many if rank < number of unknowns\ttopic::linear-algebra\nWhat three properties must a set G with operation · satisfy to be a group?\tAssociativity, existence of an identity element e, and existence of an inverse for every element (closure under · is also assumed)\ttopic::abstract-algebra\nDefine the order of a group and the order of an element g.\tThe order of a group is its number of elements |G|; the order of g is the smallest positive integer n with g^n = e (∞ if none exists)\ttopic::abstract-algebra\nState the subgroup test for a nonempty subset H of a group G.\tH ≤ G ⇔ H is nonempty and for all a, b ∈ H, ab^(−1) ∈ H\ttopic::abstract-algebra\nState Lagrange's theorem.\tIf G is a finite group and H ≤ G, then |H| divides |G|; in particular the order of any element divides |G|\ttopic::abstract-algebra\nWhat is a cyclic group?\tA group generated by a single element: G = ⟨g⟩ = {g^k : k ∈ Z}; every cyclic group is abelian\ttopic::abstract-algebra\nWhat is a (left) coset of a subgroup H in G?\tFor g ∈ G, the set gH = {gh : h ∈ H}; the distinct left cosets partition G into pieces of equal size |H|\ttopic::abstract-algebra\nWhen is a subgroup N of G normal?\tN ⊴ G ⇔ gNg^(−1) = N for all g ∈ G (equivalently gN = Ng for all g)\ttopic::abstract-algebra\nWhat is the quotient group G/N, and what condition on N is needed?\tWhen N ⊴ G, G/N is the group of cosets with (aN)(bN) = (ab)N; N must be normal for this to be well-defined\ttopic::abstract-algebra\nDefine a group homomorphism φ: G → H.\tA map with φ(ab) = φ(a)φ(b) for all a, b ∈ G; it sends identity to identity and inverses to inverses\ttopic::abstract-algebra\nWhat is a group isomorphism?\tA bijective homomorphism; if one exists, G and H are isomorphic (G ≅ H) and share all group-theoretic properties\ttopic::abstract-algebra\nDefine the kernel of a homomorphism φ: G → H, and its key properties.\tker(φ) = {g ∈ G : φ(g) = e_H}; it is a normal subgroup of G, and φ is injective ⇔ ker(φ) = {e}\ttopic::abstract-algebra\nWhat is the symmetric group S_n and its order?\tS_n is the group of all bijections (permutations) of {1,...,n} under composition; |S_n| = n!\ttopic::abstract-algebra\nWhat determines the parity (even/odd) of a permutation?\tThe parity of the number of transpositions in any decomposition; even permutations form the alternating group A_n of order n!/2\ttopic::abstract-algebra\nWhat are the defining properties of a ring (with unity)?\t(R, +) is an abelian group, multiplication is associative and distributes over addition, and there is a multiplicative identity 1\ttopic::abstract-algebra\nDefine an ideal I of a commutative ring R.\tA subgroup (I, +) such that for all r ∈ R and a ∈ I, ra ∈ I (absorbs multiplication by ring elements)\ttopic::abstract-algebra\nWhat is an integral domain?\tA commutative ring with 1 ≠ 0 that has no zero divisors: ab = 0 ⇒ a = 0 or b = 0\ttopic::abstract-algebra\nWhat is a field?\tA commutative ring with 1 ≠ 0 in which every nonzero element has a multiplicative inverse\ttopic::abstract-algebra\nFor which n is the ring Z/nZ a field?\tExactly when n is prime; Z/nZ is an integral domain ⇔ n is prime, and then it is also a field\ttopic::abstract-algebra\nWhat does a | b (a divides b) mean for integers?\tThere exists an integer k with b = ak (and a ≠ 0)\ttopic::number-theory\nState the relationship between gcd and lcm of positive integers a and b.\tgcd(a,b) · lcm(a,b) = a · b\ttopic::number-theory\nHow does the Euclidean algorithm compute gcd(a, b)?\tRepeatedly replace (a, b) by (b, a mod b) until the remainder is 0; the last nonzero remainder is gcd(a, b)\ttopic::number-theory\nWhat does a ≡ b (mod n) mean?\tn divides (a − b); equivalently a and b leave the same remainder upon division by n\ttopic::number-theory\nState Fermat's little theorem.\tIf p is prime and gcd(a, p) = 1, then a^(p−1) ≡ 1 (mod p); for any a, a^p ≡ a (mod p)\ttopic::number-theory\nDefine Euler's totient function φ(n) and give φ for a prime p and a prime power p^k.\tφ(n) counts integers in {1,...,n} coprime to n; φ(p) = p − 1 and φ(p^k) = p^k − p^(k−1)\ttopic::number-theory\nState Euler's theorem.\tIf gcd(a, n) = 1, then a^(φ(n)) ≡ 1 (mod n)\ttopic::number-theory\nState the Chinese Remainder Theorem for two moduli.\tIf gcd(m, n) = 1, the system x ≡ a (mod m), x ≡ b (mod n) has a unique solution modulo mn\ttopic::number-theory\nState the Fundamental Theorem of Arithmetic.\tEvery integer n > 1 factors into primes uniquely up to the order of the factors\ttopic::number-theory\nCompute 7^100 mod 5.\t7 ≡ 2 (mod 5), and 2^4 ≡ 1 (mod 5), so 2^100 = (2^4)^25 ≡ 1; thus 7^100 ≡ 1 (mod 5)\ttopic::number-theory\nCompute 2^10 mod 11 using Fermat's little theorem.\tBy Fermat, 2^10 ≡ 1 (mod 11) since 11 is prime and gcd(2,11) = 1\ttopic::number-theory\nState the ε–δ definition of lim(x→a) f(x) = L.\tFor every ε > 0 there exists δ > 0 such that for all x, if 0 < |x − a| < δ then |f(x) − L| < ε.\ttopic::real-analysis\nState the ε–δ definition of continuity of f at a point a.\tf is continuous at a if for every ε > 0 there exists δ > 0 such that for all x, |x − a| < δ implies |f(x) − f(a)| < ε.\ttopic::real-analysis\nWhat does it mean for a sequence (aₙ) to converge to L?\tFor every ε > 0 there exists N such that for all n ≥ N, |aₙ − L| < ε.\ttopic::real-analysis\nDefine a Cauchy sequence.\t(aₙ) is Cauchy if for every ε > 0 there exists N such that for all m, n ≥ N, |aₘ − aₙ| < ε.\ttopic::real-analysis\nWhat is meant by completeness of ℝ, and how does it relate to Cauchy sequences?\tℝ is complete: every Cauchy sequence of real numbers converges to a limit in ℝ. Equivalently, every nonempty set bounded above has a least upper bound.\ttopic::real-analysis\nState the Bolzano–Weierstrass theorem.\tEvery bounded sequence in ℝ (or ℝⁿ) has a convergent subsequence.\ttopic::real-analysis\nDefine the supremum (sup) of a nonempty set S ⊆ ℝ that is bounded above.\tsup S is the least upper bound of S: it is an upper bound M such that no number smaller than M is an upper bound. That is, M is an upper bound and for every ε > 0 there is s ∈ S with s > M − ε.\ttopic::real-analysis\nDistinguish pointwise from uniform convergence of fₙ → f on a set E.\tPointwise: for each x ∈ E and each ε > 0 there is N (depending on x) with |fₙ(x) − f(x)| < ε for n ≥ N. Uniform: N can be chosen independent of x, so sup over x of |fₙ(x) − f(x)| → 0.\ttopic::real-analysis\nState the nth-term test (divergence test) for a series Σ aₙ.\tIf Σ aₙ converges then aₙ → 0. Contrapositive: if aₙ does not tend to 0, the series diverges. (The converse fails, e.g. Σ 1/n.)\ttopic::real-analysis\nState the Intermediate Value Theorem.\tIf f is continuous on [a, b] and y is any value between f(a) and f(b), then there exists c ∈ [a, b] with f(c) = y.\ttopic::real-analysis\nState the Extreme Value Theorem.\tIf f is continuous on a closed bounded interval [a, b], then f attains a maximum and a minimum value on [a, b].\ttopic::real-analysis\nState the Mean Value Theorem.\tIf f is continuous on [a, b] and differentiable on (a, b), then there exists c ∈ (a, b) with f′(c) = (f(b) − f(a))/(b − a).\ttopic::real-analysis\nIs differentiability at a point stronger or weaker than continuity there? Give the implication.\tIf f is differentiable at a, then f is continuous at a. The converse is false (e.g. f(x) = |x| at 0 is continuous but not differentiable).\ttopic::real-analysis\nState the Monotone Convergence Theorem for sequences.\tA monotone (increasing or decreasing) sequence of real numbers converges if and only if it is bounded; an increasing bounded sequence converges to its supremum.\ttopic::real-analysis\nGive a criterion for Riemann integrability on [a, b] in terms of upper and lower sums.\tA bounded f is Riemann integrable on [a, b] iff for every ε > 0 there is a partition P with U(f, P) − L(f, P) < ε (upper and lower Darboux sums differ by less than ε).\ttopic::real-analysis\nDefine an open set in a topological space.\tA set U is open if U belongs to the topology; equivalently in a metric space, for every point x ∈ U there is r > 0 with the open ball B(x, r) ⊆ U.\ttopic::topology\nDefine a closed set in a topological space.\tA set is closed if its complement is open. Equivalently, it contains all of its limit points.\ttopic::topology\nDefine the interior, closure, and boundary of a set A.\tInterior: largest open set contained in A (union of all open subsets). Closure: smallest closed set containing A (intersection of all closed supersets). Boundary: closure(A) ∩ closure(complement of A), i.e. closure minus interior.\ttopic::topology\nDefine a basis for a topology on X.\tA collection B of open sets is a basis if every open set is a union of members of B; equivalently, for each x and open U containing x there is B ∈ 𝓑 with x ∈ B ⊆ U.\ttopic::topology\nGive the topological characterization of continuity of f : X → Y.\tf is continuous iff the preimage f⁻¹(V) is open in X for every open set V ⊆ Y (equivalently, preimages of closed sets are closed).\ttopic::topology\nDefine compactness of a topological space.\tA space is compact if every open cover has a finite subcover: for any collection of open sets whose union is X, finitely many of them already cover X.\ttopic::topology\nState the Heine–Borel theorem in ℝⁿ.\tA subset of ℝⁿ is compact if and only if it is closed and bounded.\ttopic::topology\nDefine a connected topological space.\tX is connected if it cannot be written as the union of two disjoint nonempty open sets; equivalently, the only subsets that are both open and closed are ∅ and X.\ttopic::topology\nDefine a Hausdorff (T₂) space.\tA space is Hausdorff if any two distinct points x ≠ y have disjoint open neighborhoods U ∋ x and V ∋ y with U ∩ V = ∅.\ttopic::topology\nDefine a metric space.\tA set X with a function d : X × X → [0, ∞) such that d(x, y) = 0 iff x = y, d(x, y) = d(y, x) (symmetry), and d(x, z) ≤ d(x, y) + d(y, z) (triangle inequality).\ttopic::topology\nDefine a homeomorphism between topological spaces.\tA bijection f : X → Y such that both f and f⁻¹ are continuous. If one exists, X and Y are homeomorphic (topologically equivalent).\ttopic::topology\nIs the open interval (0, 1) compact in ℝ? Justify briefly.\tNo. It is bounded but not closed, so by Heine–Borel it is not compact. E.g. the cover {(1/n, 1) : n ≥ 2} has no finite subcover.\ttopic::topology\nDefine a complex number's modulus |z| and argument arg(z) for z = x + iy.\t|z| = √(x² + y²), the distance from 0. arg(z) is the angle θ with x = |z|cos θ, y = |z|sin θ, so z = |z|(cos θ + i sin θ).\ttopic::complex-analysis\nState Euler's formula.\te^{iθ} = cos θ + i sin θ. In particular e^{iπ} + 1 = 0.\ttopic::complex-analysis\nWhat are the nth roots of unity, and what do they look like geometrically?\tThe solutions of zⁿ = 1: z = e^{2πik/n} for k = 0, 1, …, n − 1. They are n equally spaced points on the unit circle |z| = 1.\ttopic::complex-analysis\nState the Cauchy–Riemann equations for f = u + iv with z = x + iy.\tIf f is holomorphic then uₓ = v_y and u_y = −vₓ (partial derivatives). Together with continuous partials, these imply f is holomorphic.\ttopic::complex-analysis\nDefine what it means for a function to be analytic (holomorphic) on an open set.\tf is holomorphic on an open set U if it is complex-differentiable at every point of U, i.e. the limit (f(z+h) − f(z))/h exists as h → 0 (h complex) for each z ∈ U.\ttopic::complex-analysis\nState Cauchy's integral theorem.\tIf f is holomorphic on a simply connected open set and γ is a closed contour in it, then ∮_γ f(z) dz = 0.\ttopic::complex-analysis\nState Cauchy's integral formula.\tIf f is holomorphic on and inside a positively oriented simple closed contour γ, and a is interior to γ, then f(a) = (1/(2πi)) ∮_γ f(z)/(z − a) dz.\ttopic::complex-analysis\nState the residue theorem.\tIf f is holomorphic inside and on a positively oriented simple closed contour γ except at isolated singularities zₖ, then ∮_γ f(z) dz = 2πi Σ Res(f, zₖ).\ttopic::complex-analysis\nHow do you compute the residue at a simple pole z₀ of f?\tRes(f, z₀) = lim(z→z₀) (z − z₀) f(z). For f = g/h with simple zero of h at z₀, this equals g(z₀)/h′(z₀).\ttopic::complex-analysis\nFor z = x + iy, give the complex conjugate z̄ and the identity relating z, z̄, and |z|.\tz̄ = x − iy. Then z·z̄ = x² + y² = |z|², so |z| = √(z z̄).\ttopic::complex-analysis\nUnder the map w = e^z, what is the image of a horizontal line y = c (c constant) in the z-plane?\tWriting z = x + ic, w = e^x e^{ic}, so as x ranges over ℝ, w traces the ray from the origin (excluding 0) at angle c: arg(w) = c, |w| = e^x > 0.\ttopic::complex-analysis\nWhat is a sample space?\tThe set of all possible outcomes of a random experiment, usually denoted Ω or S.\ttopic::probability-statistics\nState the three Kolmogorov axioms of probability.\t1) P(A) ≥ 0 for any event A; 2) P(Ω) = 1; 3) for disjoint events, P(A ∪ B) = P(A) + P(B).\ttopic::probability-statistics\nDefine the conditional probability P(A | B).\tP(A | B) = P(A ∩ B) / P(B), provided P(B) > 0.\ttopic::probability-statistics\nState Bayes' theorem.\tP(A | B) = P(B | A) · P(A) / P(B), where P(B) > 0.\ttopic::probability-statistics\nWhen are two events A and B independent?\tWhen P(A ∩ B) = P(A) · P(B); equivalently P(A | B) = P(A).\ttopic::probability-statistics\nState the law of total probability for a partition B₁,...,Bₙ of the sample space.\tP(A) = Σ P(A | Bᵢ) · P(Bᵢ) summed over i = 1 to n.\ttopic::probability-statistics\nState the linearity of expectation for random variables X and Y.\tE[aX + bY] = a·E[X] + b·E[Y], which holds even if X and Y are not independent.\ttopic::probability-statistics\nDefine the variance of a random variable X.\tVar(X) = E[(X − μ)²] = E[X²] − (E[X])², where μ = E[X].\ttopic::probability-statistics\nWhat are the mean and variance of a Binomial(n, p) distribution?\tMean = np and variance = np(1 − p).\ttopic::probability-statistics\nState the 68-95-99.7 rule for a normal distribution.\tAbout 68% of values lie within 1σ of μ, 95% within 2σ, and 99.7% within 3σ.\ttopic::probability-statistics\nWhat are the mean and variance of a Poisson(λ) distribution?\tBoth the mean and the variance equal λ.\ttopic::probability-statistics\nFor a geometric distribution with success probability p (trials until first success), what is the expected number of trials?\tE[X] = 1/p, and variance = (1 − p)/p².\ttopic::probability-statistics\nWhen rolling two fair dice, what is P(sum = 7)?\t1/6, since 6 of the 36 equally likely outcomes sum to 7.\ttopic::probability-statistics\nWhat is the mean of a continuous Uniform(a, b) distribution?\t(a + b)/2, and its variance is (b − a)²/12.\ttopic::probability-statistics\nState the fundamental counting (multiplication) principle.\tIf one task can be done in m ways and another in n ways, the two together can be done in m · n ways.\ttopic::discrete-combinatorics\nHow many permutations (orderings) are there of n distinct objects?\tn! = n · (n−1) · (n−2) · ... · 2 · 1.\ttopic::discrete-combinatorics\nGive the formula for combinations C(n, k).\tC(n, k) = n! / (k! (n − k)!), the number of k-element subsets of an n-set.\ttopic::discrete-combinatorics\nState the binomial theorem.\t(x + y)ⁿ = Σ from k=0 to n of C(n, k) · xⁿ⁻ᵏ · yᵏ.\ttopic::discrete-combinatorics\nState the pigeonhole principle.\tIf n items are placed into m boxes with n > m, then at least one box contains at least two items.\ttopic::discrete-combinatorics\nState the inclusion-exclusion principle for two sets.\t|A ∪ B| = |A| + |B| − |A ∩ B|.\ttopic::discrete-combinatorics\nState the handshaking lemma (degree sum formula) for a graph.\tThe sum of all vertex degrees equals 2|E|, twice the number of edges.\ttopic::discrete-combinatorics\nHow many edges does a tree with n vertices have?\tExactly n − 1 edges.\ttopic::discrete-combinatorics\nState Euler's formula for a connected planar graph.\tV − E + F = 2, where V, E, F are the numbers of vertices, edges, and faces.\ttopic::discrete-combinatorics\nHow many subsets does a set with n elements have?\t2ⁿ, including the empty set and the set itself.\ttopic::discrete-combinatorics\nDescribe the idea of floating-point round-off error.\tReal numbers are stored with finite precision, so most values are rounded to the nearest representable number, introducing a relative error bounded by machine epsilon.\ttopic::numerical-analysis\nState the iteration formula for Newton's method.\tx_{n+1} = x_n − f(x_n) / f'(x_n).\ttopic::numerical-analysis\nDescribe the bisection method and its convergence.\tOn [a, b] with f(a)·f(b) < 0, repeatedly halve the interval keeping the sign change; the root is bracketed and error halves each step (linear convergence).\ttopic::numerical-analysis\nWhat is the fixed-point iteration for solving x = g(x)?\tx_{n+1} = g(x_n); it converges near a fixed point x* if |g'(x*)| < 1.\ttopic::numerical-analysis\nState the trapezoidal rule for ∫ from a to b of f(x) dx (single interval) and its error order.\t≈ (b − a)/2 · (f(a) + f(b)); the composite error is O(h²).\ttopic::numerical-analysis\nState Simpson's rule for ∫ from a to b of f(x) dx and its error order.\t≈ (b − a)/6 · (f(a) + 4f((a+b)/2) + f(b)); the composite error is O(h⁴).\ttopic::numerical-analysis\nGive the linear interpolation estimate of f(x) between points (x₀, y₀) and (x₁, y₁).\tf(x) ≈ y₀ + (y₁ − y₀)/(x₁ − x₀) · (x − x₀).\ttopic::numerical-analysis\nWhat does the condition number of a problem measure?\tHow sensitive the output is to small changes in the input; a large condition number means the problem is ill-conditioned.\ttopic::numerical-analysis\nDefine the order of convergence p of a sequence converging to x*.\tIt is the value p for which |x_{n+1} − x*| ≈ C·|x_n − x*|ᵖ; p = 1 is linear, p = 2 is quadratic (e.g., Newton's method).\ttopic::numerical-analysis\n"



def ensure_gre_math_deck(mw: "aqt.AnkiQt") -> bool:
    """Import the bundled GRE Math deck once per collection.

    Returns True only if the deck was imported on this call. Safe (and cheap) to
    call on every collection load: it no-ops once the collection has been seeded.
    """
    col = mw.col
    if col is None:
        return False
    try:
        if col.get_config(SEED_CONFIG_KEY, False):
            return False
        # If the user already has the deck, just mark as seeded (don't duplicate).
        if col.decks.by_name(DECK_NAME) is not None:
            col.set_config(SEED_CONFIG_KEY, True)
            return False

        from anki.collection import ImportCsvRequest

        fd, path = tempfile.mkstemp(prefix="gre_math_", suffix=".tsv")
        try:
            with os.fdopen(fd, "w", encoding="utf-8") as f:
                f.write(GRE_MATH_DECK_TSV)
            metadata = col.get_csv_metadata(path=path, delimiter=None)
            # Fall back to a named deck if the header didn't set one.
            if not metadata.WhichOneof("deck"):
                metadata.deck_name = DECK_NAME
            col.import_csv(ImportCsvRequest(path=path, metadata=metadata))
        finally:
            try:
                os.remove(path)
            except OSError:
                pass

        col.set_config(SEED_CONFIG_KEY, True)
        return True
    except Exception as exc:  # never let seeding break startup
        print("[mathgre] failed to seed GRE Math deck:", exc)
        return False
